From: W1700K HW2.1 build audit <noreply@example.invalid>
Subject: [PATCH] net: phy: rtl8261ce: restrict driver match to CE silicon

The RTL826x family exposes a shared 0x001cc89x identifier in one of its
Clause 45 MMDs.  PHY_ID_MATCH_MODEL alone can therefore also match sibling
parts such as RTL8261N when the dedicated CE and generic Realtek drivers are
present together.

Keep the normal vendor/model match, then distinguish the CE using the PMA/PMD
model field that config_init already validates.  This preserves the existing
RTL8261CE path while allowing the generic Realtek driver to own RTL8261N.

The extra generic match is intentional: a custom match_phy_device callback
replaces, rather than augments, phylib's default ID comparison.

--- a/drivers/net/phy/rtl8261ce/rtk_rtl8261ce_phy.c
+++ b/drivers/net/phy/rtl8261ce/rtk_rtl8261ce_phy.c
@@ -1077,6 +1077,35 @@
 	}
 
 	return 0;
+}
+
+/* Bind only genuine RTL8261CE silicon.
+ *
+ * The whole RTL826x family exposes 0x001cc89x in a shared vendor MMD, so the
+ * plain PHY_ID_MATCH_MODEL(0x001cc890) also matches sibling parts owned by the
+ * mainline realtek driver (notably the RTL8261N, PMA model 0x2f). In a build
+ * that carries BOTH drivers that double-match makes phylib fall back to the
+ * Generic Clause 45 PHY on RTL8261N units and their 10G links never come up.
+ *
+ * Distinguish by the PMA/PMD device model nibble - the same identifier
+ * rtl8261ce_config_init() validates (CE == 0x9, RTL8261N == 0x2f) - which is
+ * also the field the realtek driver keys RTL8261N on. This lets the two
+ * drivers coexist: CE claims 0x9 parts, realtek keeps the rest.
+ */
+static int rtl8261ce_match_phy_device(struct phy_device *phydev,
+				      const struct phy_driver *phydrv)
+{
+	int phyid2;
+
+	if (!phydev->is_c45 || !genphy_match_phy_device(phydev, phydrv))
+		return 0;
+
+	phyid2 = phy_read_mmd(phydev, MDIO_MMD_PMAPMD, MDIO_DEVID2);
+	if (phyid2 < 0)
+		return 0;
+
+	return FIELD_GET(RTL8261CE_PHYID2_MODEL_MASK, phyid2) ==
+	       RTL8261CE_PHYID2_MODEL;
 }
 
 /* Register the standalone CE driver. The generic Realtek driver also handles
@@ -1085,6 +1114,7 @@
 static struct phy_driver rtl8261ce_drvs[] = {
 	{
 		PHY_ID_MATCH_MODEL(RTL8261CE_PHY_ID),
+		.match_phy_device = rtl8261ce_match_phy_device,
 		.name = "Realtek RTL8261CE",
 		.probe = rtl8261ce_probe,
 		.config_init = rtl8261ce_config_init,
